TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Cascade Algorithm for Finding all Shortest Distances in a Directed Graph
AU  - Farbey, B. A.
AU  - Land, A. H.
AU  - Murchland, J. D.
Y1  - 1967/09/01
PY  - 1967
DA  - 1967/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.14.1.19
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.14.1.19
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 19
EP  - 28
VL  - 14
IS  - 1
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Matrix methods for finding shortest distances are convenient and efficient when the lengths of shortest paths are wanted between all pairs of vertices in a graph. The Cascade algorithm requires substantially fewer operations to find these distances than does the standard matrix method.
AB  - Matrix methods for finding shortest distances are convenient and efficient when the lengths of shortest paths are wanted between all pairs of vertices in a graph. The Cascade algorithm requires substantially fewer operations to find these distances than does the standard matrix method.
